In 1858 his ship made an illegal voyage to West Africa and returned with four hundred captives delivered to coastal Georgia plantations. A federal grand jury declined to indict him in April 1859."},{"number":3,"category":"legacy","header":"His slave pen became Savannah's first Black school","body":"After Sherman took Savannah in December 1864, the U.S. government gave the warehouse to the city's African American community. On January 10, 1865, Black children marched from First African Baptist Church to the building and opened Bryan School there."},{"number":4,"category":"death","header":"Killed in steamboat blast near his slave pen","body":"On June 9, 1859 the J.G. Lawton's boiler exploded fourteen miles up the Savannah River. His body was found seventy yards away in the marsh, a handkerchief still gripped in his hand."},{"number":5,"category":"family","header":"Will demanded education, sobriety, two foreign languages","body":"He instructed his children to conduct themselves as Christians, learn French and Spanish fluently, and avoid liquor and tobacco. The will took ten years to settle in court."}],"slug":"john-de-montmollin-1808"},"X00891":{"id":"X00891","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"tags":[],"sources":[{"short":"FamilySearch; de Montmollin genealogy"}],"birth":{"year":1812},"death":{"year":1887,"month":5,"day":8,"city":"Palatka","state":"Florida"},"gender":"female","number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"HD2643","date_year":1842,"date_month":1,"date_day":20,"location_city":"Savannah","location_state":"Georgia","children_ids":["HD2644","HD2645","HD2646"]}],"parents":{},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Harriet M. de Montmollin Rossignol-Belleanse","first_name":"H